problem_standardized_math:
Let
\(f(x)=h\bigl(g_1(x),g_2(x),\ldots,g_k(x)\bigr),\)\nwhere \(h:\mathbf{R}^k\to\mathbf{R}\) is convex and \(g_i:\mathbf{R}^n\to\mathbf{R}\) for \(i=1,\ldots,k\). Assume that for each \(i\), one of the following conditions holds:
\begin{itemize}
\item \(h\) is nondecreasing in its \(i\)th argument, and \(g_i\) is convex;
\item \(h\) is nonincreasing in its \(i\)th argument, and \(g_i\) is concave;
\item \(g_i\) is affine.
\end{itemize}
Show that \(f\) is convex.

You may assume that \(\operatorname{dom} h=\mathbf{R}^k\). The result also holds in the general case when the monotonicity conditions above are imposed on \(\tilde h\), the extended-value extension of \(h\).

Let \(P \in \mathbf{R}^{n\times m}\) have rank \(m\), and assume without loss of generality that
\(P=\begin{bmatrix} I \\ 0 \end{bmatrix},\)\nso that \(P^T X^{-1}P\) is the leading \(m\times m\) principal submatrix of \(X^{-1}\).

Show that
\(\left(X_{11}-X_{12}X_{22}^{-1}X_{12}^T\right)^{-1}\)\nis the leading \(m\times m\) principal submatrix of \(X^{-1}\); that is,
\(\left(X_{11}-X_{12}X_{22}^{-1}X_{12}^T\right)^{-1}=P^T X^{-1}P.\)
Hence, the convex function defined in part (c) can also be written as
\(f(X)=\log\det(P^T X^{-1}P).\)

Hint: Use the inverse formula for a symmetric block matrix:
\[
\begin{bmatrix}
A & B \\B^T & C
\end{bmatrix}^{-1}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
0 & 0 \\\\
0 & C^{-1}
\end{bmatrix}
+
\begin{bmatrix}
-I \\C^{-1}B^T
\end{bmatrix}
(A-BC^{-1}B^T)^{-1}
\begin{bmatrix}
-I \\C^{-1}B^T
\end{bmatrix}^T,
\]\nvalid when \(C\) and \(A-BC^{-1}B^T\) are invertible.

problem_finally:
Let
\[
X=\begin{bmatrix}
X_{11} & X_{12} \X_{12}^T & X_{22}
\end{bmatrix} \in \mathbf{R}^{n \times n}
\]\nbe symmetric, where
\(X_{11} \in \mathbf{R}^{m \times m}, \quad X_{12} \in \mathbf{R}^{m \times (n-m)}, \quad X_{22} \in \mathbf{R}^{(n-m) \times (n-m)}.\)
Assume that \(X\), \(X_{22}\), and the Schur complement
\(X_{11}-X_{12}X_{22}^{-1}X_{12}^T\)\nare invertible.

Let \(P \in \mathbf{R}^{n \times m}\) have rank \(m\), and assume without loss of generality that
\(P=\begin{bmatrix} I \\\\ 0 \end{bmatrix},\)\nwhere \(I\) is the \(m \times m\) identity matrix. Then \(P^T X^{-1} P\) is the leading \(m \times m\) principal submatrix of \(X^{-1}\).

1. Prove that
\(\left(X_{11}-X_{12}X_{22}^{-1}X_{12}^T\right)^{-1}\)\nis the leading \(m \times m\) principal submatrix of \(X^{-1}\). Equivalently, show that
\(\left(X_{11}-X_{12}X_{22}^{-1}X_{12}^T\right)^{-1} = P^T X^{-1} P.\)

2. Deduce that the function
\(f(X)=\log\det\left(\left(X_{11}-X_{12}X_{22}^{-1}X_{12}^T\right)^{-1}\right)\)\ncan be written as
\(f(X)=\log\det(P^T X^{-1}P).\)

Use the block inverse identity: if \(C\) and \(A-BC^{-1}B^T\) are invertible, then
\[
\begin{bmatrix}
A & B \B^T & C
\end{bmatrix}^{-1}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
0 & 0 \\\\
0 & C^{-1}
\end{bmatrix}
+
\begin{bmatrix}
-I \C^{-1}B^T
\end{bmatrix}
(A-BC^{-1}B^T)^{-1}
\begin{bmatrix}
-I \C^{-1}B^T
\end{bmatrix}^T.
\]

problem_standardized_math:
Source localization from range measurements. A signal emitted by a source at an unknown position \(x \in \mathbf{R}^n\) (\(n=2\) or \(n=3\)) is received by \(m\) sensors at known positions \(y_1,\ldots,y_m \in \mathbf{R}^n\). From the received signal strengths, noisy estimates \(d_k\) of the distances \(\|x-y_k\|_2\) are obtained. Consider the problem of estimating \(x\) by minimizing the error between the squares of the actual and observed distances:
\(\min \; f_0(x)=\sum_{k=1}^m \left(\|x-y_k\|_2^2-d_k^2\right)^2.\)
Introducing the variable \(t=x^T x\), this can be written as
\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\mbox{minimize} & \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^m \left(t-2y_k^T x+\|y_k\|_2^2-d_k^2\right)^2 \\\\
\mbox{subject to} & x^T x-t=0,
\end{array}
\tag{6}
\]\nwith variables \(x \in \mathbf{R}^n\) and \(t \in \mathbf{R}\).

Solve problem \((6)\) for the case \(m=5\), with
\(y_1=\begin{bmatrix}1.8\\\\2.5\end{bmatrix}, \qquad\ny_2=\begin{bmatrix}2.0\\\\1.7\end{bmatrix}, \qquad\ny_3=\begin{bmatrix}1.5\\\\1.5\end{bmatrix}, \qquad\ny_4=\begin{bmatrix}1.5\\\\2.0\end{bmatrix}, \qquad\ny_5=\begin{bmatrix}2.5\\\\1.5\end{bmatrix},\)\nand
\(d=(2.00,\,1.24,\,0.59,\,1.31,\,1.44).\)

You may use the fact that \(x^\star\) can be obtained from the KKT conditions for \((6)\) once the optimal multiplier \(u^\star\) for the equality constraint is known. Find \(u^\star\) by one of the following methods:
\begin{itemize}
\item derive the dual problem, express it as an SDP, and solve it using CVX;
\item reduce the KKT conditions to a nonlinear equation in \(u\), and choose the correct solution.
\end{itemize}

Consider the optimization problem
\[
\begin{aligned}
\text{minimize} \quad & f_0(x) \\\\
\text{subject to} \quad & f_i(x) \leq 0, \qquad i=1,\ldots,m,
\end{aligned}
\tag{9}
\]\nwhere the functions \(f_i : \mathbf{R}^n \to \mathbf{R}\) are differentiable and convex.

Show that
\(\phi(x)=f_0(x)+\alpha\sum_{i=1}^m \max\{0,f_i(x)\}^2,\)\nwhere \(\alpha>0\), is convex. Suppose that \(\tilde x\) minimizes \(\phi\). Show how to obtain from \(\tilde x\) a feasible point for the dual of problem \((9)\). Find the corresponding lower bound on the optimal value of \((9)\).

problem:
Exercise 4.10
Binary least-squares. We consider the non-convex least-squares approximation problem with binary constraints

\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\mbox{minimize} & \|Ax-b\|_2^2 \\
\mbox{subject to} & x_k^2 = 1,\quad k=1,\ldots,n,
\end{array}
\tag{10}
\]

where $A\in \mathbf{R}^{m\times n}$ and $b\in \mathbf{R}^m$. We assume that $\operatorname{rank}(A)=n$, i.e., $A^T A$ is nonsingular.

One possible application of this problem is as follows. A signal $\hat{x}\in \{-1,1\}^n$ is sent over a noisy channel, and received as $b=A\hat{x}+v$ where $v\sim \mathcal{N}(0,\sigma^2 I)$ is Gaussian noise. The solution of (10) is the maximum likelihood estimate of the input signal $\hat{x}$, based on the received signal $b$.

(d) Solve the dual problem (11) using CVX. Generate problem instances using the Matlab code

\begin{verbatim}
randn('state',0)
m = 50;
n = 40;
A = randn(m,n);
xhat = sign(randn(n,1));
b = A*xhat + s*randn(m,1);
\end{verbatim}

for four values of the noise level $s$: $s = 0.5$, $s = 1$, $s = 2$, $s = 3$. For each problem instance, compute suboptimal feasible solutions $x$ using the the following heuristics and compare the results.

(i) $x^{(a)} = \operatorname{sign}(x_{\mathrm{ls}})$ where $x_{\mathrm{ls}}$ is the solution of the least-squares problem

\[
\text{minimize} \quad \|Ax - b\|_2^2.
\]

(ii) $x^{(b)} = \operatorname{sign}(z)$ where $z$ is the optimal value of the variable $z$ in the SDP (11).

(iii) $x^{(c)}$ is computed from a rank-one approximation of the optimal solution of (11), as explained in part (b) above.

(iv) $x^{(d)}$ is computed by rounding 100 samples of $\mathcal{N}(z, Z - zz^T)$, as explained in part (c) above.

